        "question_7tUK8A": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What is a 360 beacon?",
            "answer": "<p>A 360 beacon is a warning light that emits illumination in all directions for maximum visibility. It’s commonly used on work trucks, utility and construction equipment, forklifts, and escort or service vehicles to alert others to your presence.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_C6iYpN": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Which vehicles can use a 360 beacon?",
            "answer": "<p>Typical applications include construction fleets, tow and recovery, snow and ice control, utilities, agriculture, security, and warehouse vehicles. Always confirm local regulations on where and how a 360‑degree beacon may be used.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_ffyGcn": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How do I choose between magnetic, permanent, or pipe mounts?",
            "answer": "<p>Magnetic mounts are fast and tool‑free for temporary use on clean steel roofs. Permanent mounts are the most secure for dedicated vehicles. Pipe mounts (often 1\" or 3/4\" NPT) are common on plows and heavy equipment and elevate the beacon above obstructions.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_Khrmfz": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Do these beacons work with 12V and 24V systems?",
            "answer": "<p>Many modern LED beacons are multi‑voltage (12–24V). Check each product page for exact ranges and current draw, and choose accessories—pigtails, adapters, or harnesses—that match your vehicle’s power.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_r49x6L": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What brightness or certification should I look for?",
            "answer": "<p>Select applications call for specific output classes (e.g., SAE Class 1 for maximum intensity). Review the listed certifications on each product and match them to your job site or fleet requirements.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_R47abB": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Which colors are available, and are there restrictions?",
            "answer": "<p>Amber is the most broadly accepted for service and construction. Red and blue are often restricted to emergency responders; green, white/clear, or purple may have niche uses. Verify local laws before ordering.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_RXk83V": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Are 360 beacons weatherproof?",
            "answer": "<p>Many models feature sealed electronics and rated ingress protection (e.g., IP65–IP67). If you work in heavy rain, wash‑down, or dust, choose higher IP ratings and add guards or gaskets as needed.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_medk3Y": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What accessories should I consider?",
            "answer": "<p>Common <strong>360 beacon and accessories</strong> bundles include replacement domes/lenses, mounting bases or pipe adapters, wire pigtails, extension leads, inline fuses, lens guards, and plug‑in switches with pattern control.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
        "question_EqD8ex": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can I synchronize multiple beacons or other lights?",
            "answer": "<p>Some beacons include sync wires or controller compatibility so multiple units flash together or alternate. Check the wiring diagram and accessory recommendations for your specific model.</p>",
            "icon": "none"
          }
        },
